'''Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha''' (とよおかかみてんじんじゃ{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}} / とよおかかみてんじんしゃ{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Heibonsha)|1983}}) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Jōtsūji-jima, Okō-chō, {{ill|lt=Nankoku|Q861621|WD=Q861621|1=Nankoku, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Kōchi Prefecture|Q134093|WD=Q134093|1=Kōchi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

It stands at the southwestern foot of Mt. Okō, where {{ill|lt=Okō Castle|Q11048926|WD=Q11048926|1=Okō Castle}} is located.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines the following one deity{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.
* {{ill|lt=Toyouke-hime|Q2983724|WD=Q2983724|lt=Yafune Toyouke-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyouke-hime}}

In ''Tosa-koku Shikishakō'', a relation is pointed out between the shrine name “Toyooka” and the deity name “Toyouke-hime (Toyouka-no-me)”{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Heibonsha)|1983}}.

=== History ===
[[File:Oko castle zenkei.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Mt. Okō with {{ill|lt=Okō Castle|Q11048926|WD=Q11048926|1=Okō Castle}}]]
Its history is unclear{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. It is said to have begun when the agricultural deity {{ill|lt=Toyouke-hime|Q2983724|WD=Q2983724|lt=Toyouke-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyouke-hime}} (Toyouke-hime-no-Mikoto) was worshiped during development of the area{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. It was originally on top of Mt. Okō, but is also said to have been moved when {{ill|lt=Okō Castle|Q11048926|WD=Q11048926|1=Okō Castle}} was built{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' compiled in {{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}} ({{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5), the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' lists “Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha” in {{ill|lt=Nagaoka District|Q1132123|WD=Q1132123|1=Nagaoka District, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|WD=Q857330|1=Tosa Province}}, and this is identified with this shrine{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. As for “Toyooka,” theories include an old name for the place name “Okō” (''{{ill|lt=Tosa Monogatari|Q11423040|WD=Q11423040|1=Tosa Monogatari}}''), “a rich hill in Nagaoka District,” or derivation from “okokufu” because of proximity to the Tosa provincial office, but it is uncertain{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. The origin of “Tenjin” is also unclear, with multiple theories{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

It is inferred to have later been revered by the {{ill|lt=Chōsokabe clan|Q981303|WD=Q981303|1=Chōsokabe clan}}, based at Okō Castle, but there are no documents and details are unclear{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was ranked as {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}{{Sfn|Toyooka Kami Tenjinsha (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

